descript.abstract: WSDELIN - Wai'anae The Nonpoint Source Pollution and Erosion Comparison Tool (N-SPECT) was developed by the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration (NOAA) Coastal Services Center to accompany the Wai'anae Ecological Characterization being developed by the Hawaii Coastal Zone Management (CZM) program. N-SPECT examines the relationship between land cover, nonpoint source pollution, and erosion. N-SPECT is an extension to Environmental Systems Research Institutes (ESRI) ArcGIS software package, version 8.3 and requires the Spatial Analyst extension. N-SPECT is designed to be portable to any watershed, provided the user has access to the necessary data. Data provided with N-SPECT are for the Wai'anae ahupua'a, the original study area located on the western side of Oahu, Hawaii. The Wai'anae ahupua'a is the collection of catchments that drain the Wai'anae mountains westward to the Wai'anae coast (west coast of Oahu, HI), including Kaluakauila, Makua, Keaau, Makaha, Kaupuni, Kamaileunu, Mailiili, Ulehawa, and Nanakuli. The data sets included in this record (see supplemental information) are components of the hydrological analysis incorporated in N-SPECT and are used "behind the scenes" to track the movement and mass of sediment and pollutants.
descript.purpose: These data sets were produced for the purpose of including the necessary topography and surface hydrology data sets with the N-SPECT package. These data sets are critical for N-SPECT functionality.
descript.supplinf: This metadata record is relevant for the following data sets: basinpoly.shp demfill flowdir nibble dem2b flowacc lsgrid wshed

srcinfo.srccontr: USGS SDTS 10m DEMs provided the source elevation data for the N-SPECT project.

procstep.procdesc: Six 7.5 x 7.5 minute SDTS 10 meter DEMs were mosaiced using the ArcINFO GRID command "mosaic" to create a single data set that covered the Wai'anae study region.
The 10 meter grid was resampled with the ArcINFO GRID command "resample" using bilinear interpolation and an output cell size of 30 meters.

DEM_30 Due to the resampling process, small coastal features such as stream mouths were closed off creating unnatural ponds. To address this issue, the ArcINFO GRID command "blockmin" was used to run a 3 x 3 filter over the DEM to record the lowest elevations within each 30 meter cell. A mask was created by encoding all cells having values greater than zero with ones, and all cells equal to zero with zeros. The mask successfully captured the small coastal features and was subsequently multiplied by the resampled DEM to produce a final 30 meter DEM that contained the coastal features.

DEMFILL The data set "demfill" was derived from the data set "dem_30" and represents an elevation data set free of sinks, or depressions that would hinder future hydrologic analyses. This was accomplished using code adapted from the ArcHydro toolset.

FLOWDIR The data set "flowdir" was derived from the data set "demfill." It represents the direction of steepest descent from cell to cell. This was accomplished using the FLOWDIRECTION command: flowdir = FlowDirection(demfill)

FLOWACC The data set "flowacc" was derived from the data set "flowdir." It represents the accumulation of uphill cells at each cell. This was accomplished using the FLOWACCUMULATION command: flowacc = FlowAccumulation(flowdir)

WSHED This process returns a grid called "wshed" that was derived using flowdir and flowacc. The maximum value from flowacc was multiplied by 0.01 to set an accumulation threshold defining small watersheds. Flowacc was then queried for all values greater than the threshold, which essentially produced a gridded stream network. The STREAMLINK command was then used to produce a grid representing the stream network in the study area where each stream segment was identified by a unique value. The WATERSHED command was then used with the streamlink and flowdir grids to produce "wshed."
BASINPOLY.SHP "Basinpoly.shp" was created from flowdir using the BASIN command. The output grid was then converted to a polygon feature class and saved as "basinpoly."

DEM2B The data set "dem2b" was derived from the data set "demfill." It is a replica of demfill but has a two cell buffer added around the periphery of the grid. This was accomplished using the following procedures: First change the calculation region to be larger by 1 grid cell, then: dem_b = Con(isnull([demfill]), focalmin([demfill]), [demfill]) Then change extent to be larger extent by 2 grid cells all directions and: dem_2b = Con(isnull([dem_b]), focalmin([dem_b]), [dem_b])

NIBBLE This grid was created directly from the flow direction grid and is essentially the same grid but contains zeros where NoData values exist in the flow direction grid. The NIBBLE command was used to ensure that all flow direction values beyond the extent of the dem were set to zero.

LSGRID Slope length was calculated by deriving the downslope angle for each cell in degrees. Next, a grid representing relative change in downslope angle was created. Areas where downslope angle exceeded 5% and the relative change in downslope angle exceeded 50% were flagged as breaks in the cumulative slope. Areas where downslope angle was less than or equal to 5% and the relative change in downslope angle exceeded 70% were also flagged as breaks in the cumulative slope. A modified flow direction grid was created where the slope break points were recoded as zeros and all other cells retained their original flow direction values. A weight grid was created where each output cell received a value of 1 if water flowed through it in a cardinal direction and 1.4142 if water flowed through it in a diagonal direction (Pythagorean Theorem). The FLOWLENGTH command was then used to sum these values along the flow paths until one of the break points, a ridge, or a pour point was encountered. This yielded the estimate of slope length lambda used to calculate the L-Factor.
The S-Factor was calculated using the following equations: Where slope < 9% S = 10.8 * (sin theta) + 0.03 Where slope > 9% S = 16.8 * (sin theta) - 0.50
The LSgrid was then produced by multiplying the the L-factor grid by the S-factor grid.
